  "doc_id": "26342",
  "text": "Fantz theorized that these kinds of early visual exploratory behaviors may be necessary for typical postnatal development. If this is the case, he reasoned that infant eye movements must be selective, peripheral and central visual structures must be sufficiently developed to support discrimination, and infants must be able to remember what they have seen [CITATION_1] . Because the demonstration of even a moderate novelty preference requires attainment of all three competencies, memory is inextricably linked to selectivity and discrimination. Following is a brief review on the development of each of these visual competencies and how they influence the emergence of VSTM.",
  "correct_citation": {
